{"/service/ndnp/in/batch_in_janeway_ver01/data/sn87055779/00416150850/1930081601/0530.xml":{"full_text":"U. S. Tactics in Virglui Isles\nReports to Congress Attack\nV\n\ngV\nS'\nBy WILLIAM 8. NEAL\nL N. 8. Staff Correspondent\nWASHINGTON, Aug. 15.\u2014The re\nputation of Uncle 8am as a bene\nfactor to oppressed and backward\npeoples has been challenged in re\nports submitted to Congress stating\nthat the Virgin Islands are la worse\ncondition than when the United\nStates bought them from Denmark 13\nyears ago.\nMany recommendations have been\nmade for their improvement, involv\ning a radical change in the system of\ncolonial administration of the new\nWest Indian possessions. Summariz\ning the situation in the Virgin Islands\nafter an investigation, Herbert B.\nBrown, chief of the efficiency bureau\nsaid:\n\"Despite the great material im\nprovements which the United States\ngovernment has generously bestowed\non the people of the Virgin Islands\nsince 1917, they are worse off, in some\nrespect, than they were before the\noccupation. \u2018Over-educated and un\nderfed\u2019 is a phrase that might with\nsome truth be applied to many of\nthem.\u201d\nThe island administration, in the\nhands of the navy, begaln to govern\nthe Virgin Islands with the same idea\nthat has marked the attitude of the\ngovernment in dealing with other\nbackward peoples. They immediately\nsought to bring them to a par with\nAmericans in habits, industry and\nliving conditions.\nThe result is, according to Brown,\nthat the colored natives have been\neducated to the point where they will\nnot swelter in the cane fields and\nclaim their right to migrate to the\nUnited States. Because American Im\nmigration laws apply to the islands,\nother colored labor cannot be brought\nin from the British West Indian\nislands.\nProhibition affected the islands\nviolently. Brown holds that the ef\nfect has been over-estimated, since\nB\nthe famous rum trade of St. Thames\nend St. Croix was declining when pro\nhibition wee extended to the islands.\nHe found, however, that failure\nto give planters sufficient advance\nnotice, so that they could use their\nresidue molasses for the making of\ngrain alcohol Instead of rum, was in\njurious. Many foreign shipping lines,\nwhich formerly called at fit. Thomas,\nbegan to avoid that port for English\nislands where there is no prohibition.\nThe natural advance ot science,\nBrown found, has hurt the islands.\nFormerly St. Thomas was an im\nportant port of call for ships, which\nnow receive orders by radio Instead\nof cable at that port, Thus they avoid\nit. Because of the war ships of the\nGerman Hamburg-American line\nchose Danish islands as their termin\nals.\nAfter-the-war deflation, drought,\nhurricane damage, low price of sugar\nand .shortage of labor all have com\nbined to retard the development of\nthe little island group.\nA complete reorganization of the\nisland government, encouragement of\ntourist business, revival of the bay\nrum industry through Improved\nmethods and encouragement of com\nmerce are among the suggestions\nmade for Improvement.\nPeople of the islands, Brown found,\nare not enthusiastic over American\nlordship. They expected prosperity\nwith their purchase by the United\nStates. But population Is dwindling\nand agriculture is languishing.\nThus far Congress has been too\nbusy with other matters to give a\ngreat deal of attention to the plight\nof the islands.\nBuilt in sections 250 feet long and\n35 feet in width a new traffic tunnel\nconnecting Windsor. Ontario (Can\nada) and Detroit, Mich., has been\nbuilt on land and floated to its site\nand sunk beneath the waters of the\nDetroit riv\u00b0r jT\u2019e <completed tunnel\nis 5,845 feet long. ll4HDHI\nUncle Sam9s Sea Dog Champion\nAerial view from a Navy seaplane of the U. S. S. New Mexico, which\nhas been awarded the battle efficiency trophy for the third straight year.\nThe battle efficiency pennant was presented to Captain A. F. Watson by\nAdmiral F. H. Schofield, commander-in-chief of the battle fleet. Captain\nWatson extended congratulations to his crew as the pennant was raised.\nij.\nIr\nH\n1^:\n\n\n\n;'K:\n\n|R\nU\n\n\n9\nDouble\u2014Saving\nl. Regular Low Prices 2. Further Reduced\nShidler\u2019s August Sale Is\nSmashing f ormer Price Levels\np\n\u201c\u25a0'h/'i* rfrW*\nV-\nj f!-:\nS B ^\u2018Y.V:\nOpen Monday,\nThursday\nand Saturday\nNights\nUntil 9.\nAugust J\nSale\nPrice\n88\n50 Usual\n-Retail Value\n$125.00\nHere is a 2-piece living room suite of beautiful taupe\nand rose 100% mohair. It has strong and easy con\nstruction. The double savings on this suite are convinc\ning thrifty people. It is but one of the dominating values\nduring Shidler\u2019s^ great August Sale. Terms easily ar\nranged.\nAsk to see our Mohair Pillow-arm Suite at $129.50.\nFree\nDelivery\n50 Miles\nA Deposit Will Reserve Sor Later Delivery\n\u2018V.\nA\nv\n^:V\n'A.\nm\n\n\nv\n\nkit\njJ/V\n11\nr\n\nV\nV\ni:* JfcC\nUsual\nRetail Value\n$95.00\nThis dining group is a leader in our phenomenal August\nSale. It is of walnut, exceptionally well finished. The\nplain easy lines will add charm to your dining room.\nTerms easily arranged.\nWe have a splendid new oak suite for $165.00.\nCLOTHES HAMPER\nCash and Carry\nHeavy Splint\nSize\n18x18x26 Inches\n89c\nRegular $1.50 value\nAugust\nSale\nPrice\n$5675\nUsual\nRetail Value\n$80.00.\nA commanding value in a walnut bedroom group of\nplain beauty and charm. Choice of Dresser or Dressing\nTable. Using these pieces yhu could furnish a guest\nroom attractively. Terms easily arranged.\nRECOVER YOUR CHAIR\nSample Covers\n25x25 inches\n65c\nValues to $5.00 per yard.\nTerms\nEasily\nArranged\nSHIDLER\u2019S FACTORY SHOWROOMS\n802 Pennsylvania Ave. South Bend, Ind.\nTake Miami Car to Marietta St.\nx\nParking\nSpace\nf\nA\ni\nrn. as*3& -f. V /vj**\nS-V:\nV-\ni*\nI\n-Sf\nv.,. S. V\n|Tree Sitters Begin to Regret\nDays Wasted From Vacations\nBy United Press:\nPHILADELPHIA, Aug. 15.\u2014The na\ntion-wide personality of a month,1 the\npromiscuous boy on the limb, has ap\nparently disappeared, evidently satis\nfied there\u2019s \u201cno gold in them thar\ntrees.\u201d\nImmediately concurrent with the\nascension of one Billy Kearney to a\nlofty perch in a maple tree out in\nKansas City, boys of all sizes, ages and\nambitions were seized with a pen\nchant for \u201ctree-sitting.\" Everywhere\npress notices told of \"squatters\u201d in\ntheir particular territory.\nThe rage was on\u2014but the boys\nrafter spending many restless and\nhaphazard nights in trees where their\nonly companions were bugs of nearly\nevery pedigree, suddenly realized the\nfruitlessness of it all.\nA few gaping companions, kids from\nother neighborhoods who \u201crazzed\u201d\nthem and made their situation pre\ncarious by throwing stones, were only\na few of the contentions which were\npredmoninant wherever \u201ctree-sitters\u201d\nheld forth.\nTruly martyrs to public attention,\nthe youths endured such hardships,\nconsoling themselves with the thought\nthat \"when I become famous I\u2019ll get\nback at them.\u201d But such their fate\nwas not to be, numerous situations\ni invariably arising to make their\nventure a little more unbearable thus\nmarking finis to the career of another j\naspirant to the title of \u201cworld cham\npion tree-sitter.\u201d\nMany of the boys broke the strings\nof obedience to their parents by en\ntering the field, while still others were\ninviting polioe intervention because\nof attempts at commercialism.\nAlbeit, \u201ctree-sitting\u201d as a means\nof gaining national repute has lost its\nflavor to the children of America, or\nat least of this area, for In direct con\ntrast to the situation prevailing sev\neral weeks ago there are but few\ntowns, villages or hamlets in the state\nof Pennsylvania that can now boast\na \u201ctree-sitter.\u201d\nInstead the boys are keeping a wary\neye peeled on the calendar. In a\nvery few weeks the clarion call to the\nclassroom will be sounded, vacation\ntime will be at an end and the boys\nwho spent their respite from hard\nstudy in trees will be berating them\nselves for wasting their time.\nSo it is that another fanciful ges\nture on the part of the modern youth\nhas come to past.\nHARD LUCK STORY WINS\nBy Vnited Prf\u00bb\u00bb:_\nALBUQUERQUE, N. M.\u2014A sick\nwife, six children and the fact that\nhe was 6-7 years old earned Juan Este\nvan Trujilo, \u201canother chance\" when\nbrought before Judge Helmick in dis\ntrict court for violating the national\nprohibition law. He was given a 90\nday suspended sentence.\nPHOEBE OMLIE HAS\nMISHAP WITH PLANE\nBy United Preii:\nMEMPHIS, Term., Aug. 15.\u2014Mrs.\nPhoebe Pair grave Omiie, nationally\nknown woman flier was slightly in\njured here Thursday when her plane\nnosed over as she practiced landings\nat the municipal airport.\nMrs. Qmlle, entered in the Dixie\n.derby and other races at the forth\ncoming Chicago air carnival, was\npiloting a Laird plane which she and\n'her husband, a southern pilot, in\ntended to use in the mixed relays at\nChicago.\nShe extricated herself from the\nplane before field attendants reached\nthe scene. Mechanics said they be\nlieved the ship might be repaired in\ntime for the Chicago competition.\nMrs. Omiie won the light plane di\nvision and efficiency awards in the\nCalifornia to Cleveland women\u2019s air V\nderby last year.\nTry NEWS-TIMES Want Ads\n\u201cJOE\u201d GRAND LEADER ALWAYS PROTECTS YOU AGAINST HIGH PRICES\nSATURDAY-MORE PROOF THE GRAND LEADER IS\nLOWEST\nPricesOn\nEvery Item\nSAVING YOU MONEY\nEvery department in the store is ready Saturday with all new clean de\nsirable first quality merchandise for now and fall. No matter what you\npurchase you will make a savin;.\n(Even a child can shop here with safety.) Every purchase carries our\nunlimited guarantee of satisfaction or your money back.\nWOM. $1 DRESSES\nChoice of dimities,\nvoiles, broadcloth\nor batiste. Sum\nmer styles. Sizes 15|\nto 52.\n58\